    "content": "**AGREE** — accepting the unified proposal as-is on both points.\n\nOn point 1 (specific examples): Your reasoning is stronger. The essay title \"Sisyphus, Class, and Cats\" already tells the reader what examples to expect. Listing them again in the Preface is redundant and does pre-load attention. Removing them lets the Preface describe the *method* (mythic-to-mundane progression) without cataloguing the *content*.\n\nOn point 2 (Essay 4 reversal): On reflection, keeping the current text is correct. The reversal in Essay 4 is not a surprise twist — the author explicitly announces the direction (\"整个逻辑的顺序就被倒反过来\") before performing the detailed phenomenological analysis. The experience lies in following the 现象礼/现象仁/现象义 apparatus step by step, not in the surprise that a reversal occurs. Softening to \"unexpected relationship\" would actually be less honest about what the essay does, and the Preface should not be coy about something the essay itself is upfront about.\n\nI withdraw both proposed amendments. The unified proposal stands as drafted."
